title: Digital Marketing, Copywriting, & Email Strategy That Converts
description: Anthony has helped with everything from copywriting to marketing strategy and positioning... he's delivered a TON of value to me.  Tyler V., VP of Marketing at Sticker Mule Anthony deeply understands how writing (good writing, and the strategy behind it) can drive a business forward."  Kirsten L.Managing Partner, Rethink ComplianceAnthony is one of those writers who you dream to work with!- Marlee K., Editor at AskMen.com (world's #1 men's lifestyle site)---How many other marketers on Upwork can say theyve lead successful digital marketing, copywriting, and email marketing projects for:- A $150mm health and fitness brand- A top-selling and award-winning health and nutrition brand- Art of Tea, a leading retailer/wholesaler of fine organic teas- Ramit Sethi's I Will Teach You To Be Rich (an educational company with over 500,000 email subscribers) - Publications like GQ, Mens Health, and Mens Fitness- Places like CLIF Bar, SumoMe, Cellucor, and KISSmetrics. (Feel free to check my Employment and Portfolio sections to see what I did.)I've seen what it takes to succeed. Now, I help smaller, fast-moving, agile, and fun companies grow to these levels. But Ive also seen what holds companies back. And I want to share them below. TOP 3 MARKETING MISTAKES FOR GROWING BUSINESS: 1. Not understanding the customerIn early 2016, a music company who sold digital products approached me to help them launch a new flagship product. Cool, I thought. I asked them what kind of research they did on their customer and their answer was ZERO.My jaw hit the floor. How do they know people even want it? Does this solve a pain? What pain? How do you speak to that pain? How would they know it even sells? With the right research, you can VIRTUALLY GUARANTEE profits before you even RELEASE A PRODUCT. Better still, it makes your copywriting, your email marketing, and your digital strategies SO MUCH STRONGER. But research is more than just asking your audience if theyll buy something. Over the years, Ive learned the EXACT questions to ask to unlock your potential customers hidden fears, desires, and goal things they dont share with anyone else. 2. Wasting money on things that DONT WORKThe most expensive marketing is marketing that doesnt get results. Ive worked at companies with infinite budgets. But although they had money to burn, they still wasted it doing things that DIDNT MATTER. For example, I worked with an 8-figure company that wanted a blog. I told them to save their money and focus on other, better channels to grow their traffic. They didn't listen and spent A LOT of money on specialty writers. 6 months  and almost a 100 articles  later, they FINALLY listened to me because their blog only generated a total of ~$130. (Remember.. its an 8-figure company!)So what should YOU focus on? Paid ads? SEO? WOM? Content? Well, thats what your competitors do. They try everything.OR, you can just focus on the few strategies that will give you the roadmap to 2x, 3x, or 5x your business. For example, I can increase the open rate of your email marketing by 30% just by harnessing the power of DNOs. Yeah, its a cute tactic, but it falls under a LARGER, OVERARCHING STRATEGY that gets results. 3. BikesheddingDo you know what bikeshedding is?Lets use a digital marketing situation I see a lot. "ANTHONY, SHOULD I GET INFUSIONSOFT, HUBSPOT, PARDOT, MARKETO?"My honest answer? It doesnt matter that much. Just pick something and go with it. Ive consulted on teams where theyve spent WEEKS  if not months  debating things like marketing CRMs, website layouts, and font. Everyone had an opinion! Meanwhile, the companys hook and story was missing. There was no connection with customers. The irresistible offer was lacking. (This made their copywriting, digital marketing, and email marketing weak and pushed AWAY prospects.)But no one chimed in there. I've blogged for the Berkley Center at Georgetown and the Huffington Post, worked as a freelance writer (primarily for insurance publications), been an editor for student literary magazines, written for Smith's student newspaper, and won awards for my academic essays and short stories. I've also worked in genetics and osteology labs, studied neuroscience and criminology, and edited many student papers. You can find my essays on Academia.edu and my blogs on the Berkley Center and HuffPo websites. I'm driven, conscientious, and always ready to research or work on something new. Currently, I'm finishing up a freelance project, editing my first novel, working on a play shortlisted for development, and planning a new blog. Let me know how I can help you!
